for a classi load balancer we need a launch template first

#!/bin/bash
# Install Apache HTTP server
yum install httpd -y

# Start and enable Apache to run on boot
systemctl start httpd
systemctl enable httpd

# Fetch instance details
HOSTNAME=$(hostname)
IP_ADDRESS=$(hostname -I | awk '{print $1}')
UPTIME=$(uptime -p)
DATE=$(date)
INSTANCE_ID=$(curl -s http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/instance-id)
AZ=$(curl -s http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/placement/availability-zone)

# Create HTML content
cat <<EOF > /var/www/html/index.html
<html>
<head>
    <title>Load Balancer Instance</title>
    <style>
        body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; text-align: center; background-color: #f0f0f0; }
        h1 { color: #2e6da4; }
        table { margin: auto; border-collapse: collapse; }
        td, th { border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; }
        th { background-color: #2e6da4; color: white; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>This is my Load Balancer instance: $HOSTNAME</h1>
    <p>Served from: <strong>$AZ</strong></p>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Instance ID</th><td>$INSTANCE_ID</td></tr>
        <tr><th>IP Address</th><td>$IP_ADDRESS</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Uptime</th><td>$UPTIME</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Current Date</th><td>$DATE</td></tr>
    </table>
</body>
</html>


created a template not an instance


step2: now going to create a load balancer

select classi lb
name: clb
select, internet-facing as a shckeme; then only you can hit IP on browser

ste3: by using autoscaling group we are going to connect our launch template and load balancer

create auto scaling group
name;ASG
select your template here
while attaching to the load balancer
1. for classic easey
2 but for other application/gateway/network lb - you need a target group to connect 

3. You can resize your Auto Scaling group manually or automatically
min 2 and max 4

4, you can check with public ip of created instance or with load balancer DNS

